43
00:02:11,770 --> 00:02:15,350
that epithelial cell will use all of its
machinery to make virus.

44
00:02:16,360 --> 00:02:19,910
Now as the infection progresses, viruses
will spread to neighbouring,

45
00:02:19,910 --> 00:02:23,520
unaffected cells, effecting more of the
epithelial lining.

46
00:02:23,520 --> 00:02:25,960
Infected cells begin to sense the foreign
invaders,

47
00:02:25,960 --> 00:02:30,720
by detecting pathogen associated molecular
patterns, or PAMPs.

48
00:02:30,720 --> 00:02:34,300
This represents the beginning of innate
immune defense.

49
00:02:34,300 --> 00:02:38,610
The infected epithelial cells send signals
to try and stop the infection.

50
00:02:38,610 --> 00:02:42,240
The signals include secretion of
Interferon, other cytokines, and

51
00:02:42,240 --> 00:02:47,952
chemokines, to recruit immune cells into
the local area, which then extravisate.

52
00:02:47,952 --> 00:02:52,900
These cytokines and chemokines also
stimulate mucus production and release.

53
00:02:53,990 --> 00:02:59,330
All of this results in increases in
vascular permeability,

54
00:02:59,330 --> 00:03:03,650
which cause swelling of the walls of the
airway,

55
00:03:03,650 --> 00:03:08,420
it increases inflammatory cell
infiltration into the interstitial tissue,

56
00:03:08,420 --> 00:03:11,840
and it fills up the airway lumen with
mucus and cellular debris.

57
00:03:11,840 --> 00:03:15,720
What the patient notices is a lot of
swelling, mucus and debris.

58
00:03:17,060 --> 00:03:18,460
In order to exit,

59
00:03:18,460 --> 00:03:21,165
viruses need to be released back into the
lumen of the airway.

60
00:03:21,165 --> 00:03:26,567
Non-enveloped viruses, or naked capsids,
exit cells by lysing the cell.

61
00:03:26,567 --> 00:03:32,067
Virions then enter into the environment
within mucus secretions and droplets.

